    {
      "text": "50-year-old man presents with complaints of blood and mucus in thin ribbon like stool, tenesmus and weight loss. MRI abdomen shows bowel wall thickening in descending colon and perirectal fat thickening and enlarged lymph nodes. First differential diagnosis is?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Colorectal cancer"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Ulcerative colitis"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Microscopic colitis"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Crohn’s disease"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer is A: <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">Colorectal</span> cancer</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The presence of blood and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ab75ea330616927771938a64f8ebd6\">mucus</span> in thin ribbon-like stools, along with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"81835594ca1692777200eff0d7fb81\">tenesmus</span> (feeling of incomplete evacuation) and weight loss, are classical symptoms suspicious for a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> malignancy.</li>\n\t<li>MRI findings supporting <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f04bf2125316927771847bfe139191\">colorectal</span> cancer include:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Bowel wall thickening which represents tumour mass.</li>\n\t\t<li>Perirectal fat thickening indicative of tumour extension beyond the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> wall.</li>\n\t\t<li>Enlarged <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4df97a6cbf169277719172fd1af767\">lymph</span> nodes, which likely represent nodal metastases</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>Microscopic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e6955110f21692777184d2090a400c\">colitis</span> is a chronic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9d21dd5d3116927771907405b181bc\">inflammatory</span> condition of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0fce15e71f1692777184feb9af5303\">colon</span> that causes persistent, non-bloody watery diarrhea. There are two main types of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"79067cb33316927771926965c3c0b5\">microscopic</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e6955110f21692777184d2090a400c\">colitis</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"79dbeeeba41692777184e63d6d214e\">collagenous</span> and lymphocytic colitis.</li>\n\t<li>Crohn’s disease can cause <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> wall thickening and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"344bcb4e391692777191307c1e0074\">lymphadenopathy</span> but often shows skip lesions rather than continuous involvement and is usually associated with other signs such as strictures, fistulas, or creeping fat rather than primarily <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9626003516169277719575ac559a91\">perirectal</span> fat thickening</li>\n</ul>",
      "question_images": [],
      "explanation_video": null,
      "explanation_images": [],
      "explanation_audio_eng": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/iNdR9gaN2TyCLFttd0wT1755293598.mp3",
      "explanation_audio_hin": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/Crgnnmx4RbhOWEaGzvCJ1755293727.mp3"
