    },
    {
      "text": "32-year-old male with ulcerative colitis presents with increased frequency of bloody diarrhea (8–10 times/day) for the past week, associated with abdominal pain and fever. On examination, his pulse is 110/min, BP 100/60 mmHg, temperature 38.2°C. Abdominal examination reveals diffuse tenderness without guarding. Labs are shown below. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management\n\nHemoglobin: 9.8 g/dL\n\nESR: 68 mm/hr\n\nCRP: markedly elevated\n\nStool culture: negative for pathogens",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Oral mesalamine"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Sulfasalazine enema"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Initiate intravenous corticosteroids"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Schedule Proctolectomy immediately"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer is C: initiate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"27b78a96071692777190f4dfb93430\">intravenous</span> corticosteroids </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>By Truelove and Witts criteria, the patient is having severe <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b5a5dcf4021692777187e3c0d2d47d\">exacerbation</span> of UC that will require IV steroids followed by oral followed by enemas of steroids.</li>\n</ul>",
